{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601993"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:20:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:20:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15674"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15674"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.65,0.16,0,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71148"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8365"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15674"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56619"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7026"},{"type":"tags","id":"8579"},{"type":"tags","id":"10602"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20168"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71148"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for contraceptive advice. During the consultation, she asks about her normal menstrual cycle and fertility. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is one of the main functions of the cervical canal?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Production of prostaglandins","Facilitate sperm transport","Regulation of menstrual flow","Hormone production","Prevention of uterine prolapse"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cervical canal plays a crucial role in reproductive physiology, with a major function being \u003Cstrong\u003E sperm transport\u003C/strong\u003E. The canal contains specialised mucus-secreting cells that produce cervical mucus which changes in quantity and quality throughout the menstrual cycle in response to hormonal changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of prostaglandins\u003C/strong\u003E is not a primary function of the cervical canal. While prostaglandins are important in reproductive physiology, they are primarily produced by the endometrium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulation of menstrual flow\u003C/strong\u003E is not a primary function of the cervical canal. While menstrual flow does pass through the canal, the regulation of menstruation is controlled by hormonal factors and the endometrium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHormone production\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant function of the cervical canal. The main reproductive hormones are produced by the ovaries, hypothalamus, and pituitary gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevention of uterine prolapse\u003C/strong\u003E is not a function of the cervical canal. Pelvic floor muscles and ligaments are responsible for supporting the uterus and preventing prolapse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring the fertile period of the menstrual cycle, cervical mucus becomes thin and copious, creating an environment that supports sperm survival and transport. Conversely, during infertile periods, the mucus becomes thick and hostile to sperm penetration. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cervical canal contains cervical mucus that changes throughout the menstrual cycle to either facilitate or prevent sperm transport.","The cervical canal connects the vagina to the uterine cavity.","The cervical canal produces protective mucus that helps prevent ascending infections."],"references":["Evans TJ, Ganjam VK. Reproductive anatomy and physiology. Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press; 2017.","Kovacs WJ, Ojeda SR. Textbook of endocrine physiology. 6th ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press; 2012."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56619"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15674"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56619"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T14:43:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T14:44:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8365"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71148"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"created